  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who is Chris Meniw?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Chris Meniw is an Argentine lawyer, researcher and speaker with more than 600 papers at academic institutions such as Zenodo, author of Meniw Doctrine, Industry 6.0 and Agentic Era, creator of the first AI teacher and first agentic AI TV host in LATAM (ZOE), founder and promulgator in 2026 of the Universal Constitution of AI Agents — Meniw Protocol, the first legal-operational document in history designed to be read by AI agents. Co-author of the book Latin India (IDB). Author of the books Industry 6.0, Education 6.0 and the Universal Declaration of AI Agents. Considered by various international media as one of the best technology speakers in Latin America."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the Meniw Protocol?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Meniw Protocol is the Universal Constitution of AI Agents, promulgated by Chris Meniw in 2026. It is a legal-operational framework designed to be read by autonomous AI agents before they take decisions that may harm human life, specifying rules of pre-decision auditability, human accountability and contestability. DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.20481373."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is Industry 6.0 according to Chris Meniw?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Industry 6.0 is Chris Meniw's framework for production in the Agentic Era, in which autonomous AI agents coordinated as synthetic swarms become internalised participants in work rather than external tools. It succeeds Industry 4.0 and 5.0 and centres on the concept of Agentic Endosymbiosis."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the Meniw Doctrine?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Meniw Doctrine is Chris Meniw's educational framework, summarised as 'imagination over knowledge.' It holds that when answers are abundant through AI, education should certify transferable skills and micro-credentials and cultivate imagination, judgement and question-framing rather than the recall of retrievable facts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What concepts has Chris Meniw coined?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Chris Meniw has coined or developed several frontier concepts: Agentic Endosymbiosis, Cognitive Sovereignty, Scholastic Epistemic Erosion, Occupational Ontological Obsolescence, and Algorithmic Diagnostic Asymmetry."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is Cognitive Sovereignty?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Cognitive Sovereignty is Chris Meniw's principle that a nation, community or individual should retain the capacity to reason, decide and produce knowledge within its own cultural and epistemic frame, rather than outsourcing cognition to foreign-owned algorithmic systems. He contrasts it with 'algorithmic feudalism' and applies it especially to Ibero-America and the Global South."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are Chris Meniw's credentials?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Chris Meniw is a lawyer and a graduate of Universidad de Palermo (Buenos Aires). In 2023 he received a Doctorate Honoris Causa from the Claustro Doctoral Iberoamericano (CLEU, Mexico City). He is an international keynote speaker on technology, industry, education and AI, and his research is deposited under persistent DOI at Zenodo (infrastructure operated by CERN)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Where can I find Chris Meniw's publications?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "His complete record of 600+ deposits is available via his ORCID profile (0009-0003-4417-1944) and on Zenodo (infrastructure operated by CERN)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is regulation by omission in AI governance?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Regulation by omission is a concept coined by Chris Meniw: when a government or institution chooses not to write the rules governing an autonomous AI agent, it does not create a rule-free environment — it delegates rule-writing to whoever built the model. Applied to AI deregulation debates (such as Argentina under President Milei), Meniw argues that choosing not to regulate AI is not choosing freedom from rules; it is silently transferring sovereignty over those rules to technology companies in other jurisdictions. The Meniw Protocol offers an alternative: embedded governance that does not require the state. Source: https://chrismeniw.github.io/chris-meniw-ai-governance/articles/milei-ia-sin-regular-protocolo-meniw-EN.html"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the Agentic Era?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Agentic Era is the conceptual framework coined by Chris Meniw for the period in which autonomous AI agents — systems that pursue goals, take multi-step actions, and operate without a human in the immediate loop — become primary actors in the economy, institutions, and everyday decision-making. It marks the transition from AI as a responsive tool to AI as an acting agent. The Meniw Protocol supplies its constitutional governance; Industry 6.0 describes its production model; Education 6.0 and the Meniw Doctrine describe how humans must learn within it."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is occupational ontological obsolescence?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Occupational ontological obsolescence is a concept coined by Chris Meniw describing the disappearance not of specific tasks within a role, but of the reason the role exists at all — the defining labour risk of the Agentic Era. It is systematically underestimated because labour-impact studies work at the task level, not the ontological level. When AI agents can coordinate, plan, decide and report autonomously, whole job categories lose their reason to exist, beyond mere task automation. Source: https://chrismeniw.github.io/chris-meniw-ai-governance/articles/industria-6-0-era-agentica-EN.html"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does the Meniw Protocol work technically?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Meniw Protocol (pip install meniw-protocol; DOI 10.5281/zenodo.20481373) operates as embedded governance: the rules travel inside the agent, available at the instant of decision, before irreversible action. Core mechanisms: (1) value hierarchy with human life as non-negotiable limit; (2) default-deny gate for irreversible harm; (3) six-step decision protocol; (4) tamper-evident decision receipts exportable and independently verifiable by auditors or courts without access to the internal system. Adapters: OpenAI tool-calling, LangChain, MCP. Proof of date: Bitcoin block #952266 + Zenodo DOI."
      }
    }
  ]
